WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.160
Hey everybody, I'm Winston Chang, I work at Posit on the Shiny team, and I'm going to

00:00:10.160 --> 00:00:13.840
show you something really cool that we've made recently called Shiny Assistant.

00:00:13.840 --> 00:00:17.879
What Shiny Assistant does is it will help you build Shiny applications and help you

00:00:17.879 --> 00:00:18.879
get started.

00:00:18.879 --> 00:00:22.299
Sometimes the hardest part about building a new application is just like getting over

00:00:22.299 --> 00:00:27.280
the initial hump and just like, how do I get from turning this idea into some sort of working

00:00:27.280 --> 00:00:28.280
prototype.

00:00:28.280 --> 00:00:32.320
I've got Shiny Assistant right here and it's a chat interface to begin with, but I can

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:35.639
ask it to do things like I will ask it to build an application.

00:00:35.639 --> 00:00:38.279
I've been thinking about how much does it cost to buy a home?

00:00:38.279 --> 00:00:40.759
So I thought it'd be really useful to have a mortgage calculator.

00:00:40.759 --> 00:00:45.000
If I were to build that myself by hand, that would take a while, but I'm going to use Shiny

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:47.160
Assistant to help me get started here.

00:00:47.160 --> 00:00:59.880
So let's say, build an application which calculates mortgage payments.

00:00:59.880 --> 00:01:04.720
That's all I said, just one sentence, build an application which calculates mortgage payments.

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:12.239
So it starts up Shiny live here, it's running in the browser, and we have a mortgage payment

00:01:12.239 --> 00:01:13.239
calculator.

00:01:13.239 --> 00:01:14.400
So hit the calculate button.

00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:20.320
So here we go, if the loan amount was $200,000 and the interest rate was 3.5%, the monthly

00:01:20.320 --> 00:01:25.919
payment would be about $900 and the total payments would be about $300,000.

00:01:25.919 --> 00:01:31.120
And we can change these amounts, let's say the loan amount was $500,000, the interest

00:01:31.120 --> 00:01:36.000
rate was 6%, which is closer to reality these days, and it will give me some new numbers

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:37.000
here.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:41.839
Now I can put these numbers in the application itself, so as the starting values, because

00:01:41.839 --> 00:01:47.760
these are more realistic starting values, put them there, hit this rerun app button,

00:01:47.760 --> 00:01:51.480
this play button, to rerun it, and as you can see, those are now the default starting

00:01:51.480 --> 00:01:52.480
values.

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:55.320
Hit calculate, and there it is.

00:01:55.320 --> 00:01:59.519
OK, so that's really useful, but let's say I want to add a few more things to this app.

00:01:59.519 --> 00:02:03.959
Let's say I want to have a plot of the remaining principal.

00:02:03.959 --> 00:02:16.119
So I'll just ask it to do that and let it do its thing.

00:02:16.119 --> 00:02:20.759
OK, so let's hit the calculate button again, and here we go.

00:02:20.759 --> 00:02:27.479
So this is the remaining principal for time, it starts at $500,000, and after 360 payments

00:02:27.479 --> 00:02:29.440
or 30 years, that goes down to zero.

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:33.039
That's really helpful, and let's say I want a little bit more detailed information, I

00:02:33.119 --> 00:02:38.199
can ask it to add an amortization table.

00:02:38.199 --> 00:02:43.520
So the amortization table, if you're not familiar, just shows how much interest in principal

00:02:43.520 --> 00:02:49.479
is being paid and is remaining at each payment.

00:02:49.479 --> 00:02:56.759
All right, hit calculate again, and I'll just show more entries here.

00:02:56.759 --> 00:03:01.639
So at the beginning, with this payment, about $3,000, most of it's going to interest, and

00:03:01.639 --> 00:03:05.039
just a little bit of it is going to principal, and then this is the remaining balance on

00:03:05.039 --> 00:03:07.080
the loan.

00:03:07.080 --> 00:03:11.839
And over time, it's going to be 360 payments total, eventually that's going to go all the

00:03:11.839 --> 00:03:12.839
way down to zero.

00:03:12.839 --> 00:03:17.440
There you are, this is an app for calculating mortgage payments, and while you could do

00:03:17.440 --> 00:03:22.600
this by hand, you can see that building something like this with Shiny Assistant is way, way

00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:23.600
faster.

00:03:23.600 --> 00:03:28.720
Now, of course, if you're really going to build a real app, you want to check the math,

00:03:29.039 --> 00:03:33.479
the math in these calculations here to make sure that everything is right, because it

00:03:33.479 --> 00:03:35.080
won't always get all the details right.

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:39.220
It's not perfect, it might have some bugs in the code, but it will help you get started

00:03:39.220 --> 00:03:43.639
on applications like this way, way faster than you might otherwise be able to do.

00:03:43.639 --> 00:03:46.880
If you want to give Shiny Assistant a try, check out the link that's in the description.

00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:51.320
Right now, it's sort of experimental, so you'll be put on a waiting list, but we will try

00:03:51.320 --> 00:03:54.119
to get you off the waiting list as soon as possible.

00:03:54.119 --> 00:03:58.000
Yeah, and have fun with this, you know, can't wait to see what kind of cool ideas people

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:01.800
have and see you turn those things, those ideas into reality.

